    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6c77256f_28967733",
        "filename": "minidump/minidump_memory_writer.h",
        "patchSetId": 22
      },
      "lineNbr": 164,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144260
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-01T20:21:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Right, if we added multiple non-owned ranges that overlap, we would still emit a bad dump. Hopefully in practice this doesn\u0027t happen as it should just be stacks and some select relevant code memory that we capture.\n\n(We do drop owned that overlap non-owned as I\u0027m sure you saw, so at least that is handled.)\n\nTaking another look at AddMemorySnapshot() callers, another way it could break (Windows-only :() is via CrashpadInfo::set_extra_memory_ranges(). If the user points into somewhere we\u0027re already gathering, I think we could emit overlapping ranges. It doesn\u0027t look like that\u0027s actually used in Chromium though. There may be other cases though. Anyway, added some notes here.\n\n...\n\n...\n\nWait, scratch all that! AddMemorySnapshot() is what we _want_ to use, oops. I was confused. OK, yes, this is fairly minor then, as the only non-owned memory is from MinidumpThreadWriter for the stack, so in practice we shouldn\u0027t have a problem.",
      "parentUuid": "3a0a66fe_b40f3aac",
      "revId": "dc681b6f74bcf72f9659840b48f45974ec12466e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
