    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "eb1330a2_c4cc0df3",
        "filename": "snapshot/memory_snapshot.cc",
        "patchSetId": 22
      },
      "lineNbr": 52,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144260
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-01T20:21:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Good question, I\u0027m not exactly sure what I was thinking.\n\nLooking back at how it\u0027s used in CoalesceOwnedMemory(), my theory for what I was thinking way back is probably that I didn\u0027t want any zero-sized ranges in the final output... Letting either-but-not-both be zero-sized works beacuse it collapses away the zero-sized one.\n\nBoth-zero almost works, but then doesn\u0027t quite in the degenerate case if there\u0027s only empty ranges because then the last one wouldn\u0027t collapse... So, it probably makes more sense to completely disallow empty ranges in this function, and have CoalesceOwnedMemory() filter empty ranges beforehand. I think.",
      "parentUuid": "f8ba140c_5c5c0aef",
      "revId": "dc681b6f74bcf72f9659840b48f45974ec12466e",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
